Headlines.Headline: MARKET TALK: Slowing Retail Auto-Parts Sales a Drag on LKQ -Baird

PARAGRAPH.#text: 11:37 EDT - Investors are driving LKQ's shares lower as Baird notes spending has slowed in the auto-parts retail sector. Mild winter and early spring lessened vehicle wear-and-tear, curbing sales of maintenance and failure parts at O'Reilly Automotive (ORLY), AutoZone (AZO), Advance Auto Parts (AAP) and Monroe Muffler (MRO). Comments echo Tuesday's warning from ORLY, which dragged the sector lower yesterday. Although LKQ deals primarily in collision parts, Baird doubts it'll be immune to broader headwinds as consumers defer maintenance. Firm cut LKQ to neutral from outperform as the stock approaches its $33.96 price target. Shares down 5.9% at $31.97, cutting their gains for the year to 6%. (melodie.warner@dowjones.com)

Headlines.Author: William L. Watts
Headlines.Headline: US Stock Futures Slump On Growth Fears

PARAGRAPH.#text: By William L. Watts FRANKFURT (MarketWatch)--U.S. stock index futures fell Monday, with another round of lackluster Chinese survey data adding to worries over global growth prospects, aggravated by last week's lackluster May U.S. nonfarm payrolls data and continued worries over the euro-zone debt crisis. Futures on the Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 50 points to 12,053. S&P 500 Index futures declined 2.2 points to 1,271.70, while Nasdaq 100 futures lost 3 points to 2,452. China's nonmanufacturing Purchasing Manager's Index for May fell to 55.2 on a 100-point scale in April, according to an official survey released Sunday, easing from 56.1 in April and undercutting hopes the service sector could take up some slack from slowing manufacturing activity.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: US Stock Futures Slump On Growth Fears

Headlines.Author: Joan E. Solsman
Headlines.Headline: O'Reilly's CSK To Pay $20.9M To Resolve DOJ Securities Violations

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES CSK Auto Corp., the auto-parts retailer now part of O'Reilly Automotive Inc. ORLY, agreed to pay a $20.9 million penalty to resolve securities violations linked to an earnings manipulation scheme, the U.S. Department of Justice said. In the scheme, which occurred before O'Reilly bought CSK, former CSK employees concealed $52 million in vendor rebates that the company had claimed as income but were never actually collected, according to the department. Workers also double-billed vendors and lied to the company's independent auditor to cover up their tracks.

Headlines.Author: John Kell
Headlines.Headline: O'Reilly Automotive Adds $500 Million To Stock-Repurchase Program

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES O'Reilly Automotive Inc.'s ORLY board added $500 million to the auto-parts retailer's stock-repurchase program, doubling the total authorized so far this year. Chief Financial Officer Tom McFall said the move was enacted to "enhance shareholder value and driven by our strong free cash flow." O'Reilly joined a number of firms that enacted or boosted stock-repurchase plans to appeal to investors. In January, O'Reilly had authorized a repurchase program of $500 million. Since its inception, McFall said O'Reilly has repurchased over 7 million shares for a total investment of over $400 million.
